    {
      "id": "cff72f3b_b4ee7f18",
      "file_path": "src/onaptests/configuration/cds_resource_resolution_settings.py",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 4,
      "message": "Not really. What we want is to have all data from `settings` and override some of them. Unfortunately with your proposals is not possible. I'll show you an example:\nWe have 2 settings files:\n`settings.py`:\nNAME = \"Joe\"\nAGE = 21\n\n`settings_test.py`:\nfrom settings import *\nNAME = \"Ben\"\n\nand a `test.py`:\nimport settings_test as settings\nprint(f\"{settings.NAME} {settings.AGE}\")\n\nWhen you execute a code using `python3.8 test.py` the result is:\nBen 21\n\nbut if we change `settings_test.py` into:\nimport settings\nNAME = \"Ben\"\n\nand try to execute `python3.8 test.py` we will get\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"test.py\", line 2, in <module>\n    print(f\"{settings.NAME} {settings.AGE}\")\nAttributeError: module 'settings_test' has no attribute 'AGE'\n\nI know using wildcard import should be avoided, but in some cases it's not a bad practice",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6079,
        "name": "Micha? Jagie??o",
        "display_name": "Michal Jagiello",
        "email": "michal.jagiello@t-mobile.pl",
        "username": "MichalJagielloTMPL"
      },
      "updated": "2021-07-30 11:42:10.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "7d4b63c4_684174ef",
      "unresolved": true
    },
